            <p>DR. D. STERN&#44;<lb/>
                EDITOR JEWISH TRIBUNE.<lb/></p>
            <p><del>Natchez&#44; Miss.</del> Wilkesbarre Pa.&#44; Sept. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1882.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear and Reverend Sir&#58; You are perfectly right<lb/> in your supposition that I have been away<lb/> from home&#59; my presence in St. Louis was<lb/> announced in the <hi rend="underline">Tribune</hi> some weeks ago<lb/> yesterday I returned and found an English<lb/> letter from your son and a Hebrew postal card<lb/> from you.  Your son&#39;s letter has already been<lb/> forwarded for publication.  But <hi rend="underline">your</hi> English<lb/> letter whereof you speak in your last postal card<lb/> has not reached me&#44; and it is very probable<lb/> that it has been forwarded to St. Louis and will<lb/> be returned to me in a few days.<lb/></p>
            <p>And now my dear Rabbi&#44; permit me to say<lb/> to you that my respect for your sincere piety<lb/> and earnest convictions would have remained<lb/> unaltered even if you had been the author<lb/> of that bitter article.  We are all entitled to our<lb/> honest convictions in the realm of religion&#44; and<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I know of no authority in Judaism that can<lb/> abridge that freedom.  &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  It is<lb/> perhaps superfluous for me to say that I have<lb/> not the least personal ill&#45;will either against<lb/> yourself or your son&#44; for I believe that with<lb/> all the differences that exist between us we<lb/> can imitate the example of those whom<lb/> tradition informs us that &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#41;.  Let us leave personal animosity for<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Let us hope that at<lb/> the beginning of the new year a new spirit may<lb/> enter into our Jewish affairs&#44; and that true<lb/> peace based upon respect for honest opinion<lb/> may prevail in our midst.<lb/></p>
            <p>&#33;&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours truly<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Dr. David Stern</hi>.<lb/></p>
        </body>
